  "opinion": "As a 32-year-old self-employed nurse living in Rome, married with one child, and a native-born Italian who practices Hinduism, my perspective on managing fake content on social media is shaped by my professional background and personal values. I use social media only a few times monthly, primarily to stay connected with family and friends, and to follow my hobbies like gardening and calcio. This limited engagement means I encounter fake content less frequently, but when I do, I approach it with the same care and diligence I apply in my nursing work. In healthcare, accuracy and trust are paramount, and I extend this mindset to online interactions. To manage fake content, I rely on critical thinking and verification. Before sharing or reacting to any information, I check multiple reliable sources, such as official health organizations or reputable news outlets, to confirm its validity. This habit stems from my moderate conscientiousness and agreeableness, which drive me to be responsible and considerate in my actions. My creative psychological feature helps me think outside the box when assessing content, looking for inconsistencies or emotional manipulation tactics often used in fake posts. I also educate my family, especially my child, about digital literacy, emphasizing the importance of questioning sources and not spreading unverified information. Given my high extraversion, I enjoy discussing these issues in person with friends during calcio matches or gardening sessions, where we share tips and experiences. My low openness means I prefer sticking to trusted methods and avoid experimenting with new platforms that might have higher risks of fake content. Overall, I believe that personal responsibility, combined with community support and education, is key to dealing with fake content effectively, ensuring that social media remains a positive space for genuine connections.",
